03975nam a22004575i 9780228002550DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280025507 a10.1515/97802280025502doi  a(DE-B1597)657607  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV5822.C3 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a362.32231 aGuba, David A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaming Cannabis :bDrugs and Empire in Nineteenth-Century France /cDavid A. Guba. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIntoxicating Histories ;v100tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Hashish, Islam, and Violence in the French Colonial Mind -- tCompeting Strains: The Two Histories of Cannabis in Early Modern France -- tJacques-François “Abdallah” Menou, Colonial Mimicry, and the First Anti-Cannabis Law in French History -- tAntoine Isaac Silvestre de Sacy and the Myth of the Hachichins: Orientalizing Hashish in France, 1800–40 -- t“A Drug Not to Be Neglected”: Medicalizing Hashish in France, 1810–50 -- t“Empire of Hallucinations and Illusions”: De-medicalizing Hashish in France, 1840–60 -- tThe Hachichins of Algiers: The Criminalization of Hashish in French Algeria, 1840–80 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite having the highest rates of cannabis use in the continent, France enforces the most repressive laws against the drug in all of Europe. Perhaps surprisingly, France was once the epicentre of a global movement to medicalize cannabis, specifically hashish, in the treatment of disease. In Taming Cannabis David Guba examines how nineteenth-century French authorities routinely blamed hashish consumption, especially among Muslim North Africans, for behaviour deemed violent and threatening to the social order. This association of hashish with violence became the primary impetus for French pharmacists and physicians to tame the drug and deploy it in the homeopathic treatment of mental illness and epidemic disease during the 1830s and 1840s. Initially heralded as a wonder drug capable of curing insanity, cholera, and the plague, hashish was deemed ineffective against these diseases and fell out of repute by the middle 1850s. The association between hashish and Muslim violence, however, remained and became codified in French colonial medicine and law by the 1860s: authorities framed hashish as a significant cause of mental illness, violence, and anti-state resistance among indigenous Algerians. As the French government looks to reform the nation's drug laws to address the rise in drug-related incarceration and the growing popular demand for cannabis legalization, Taming Cannabis provides a timely and fascinating exploration of the largely untold and living history of cannabis in colonial France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228002550?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228002550423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228002550/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles